<H3> <TI>   Yemeni Arab League Delegate Presents Credentials </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yemeni Arab League Delegate Presents Credentials </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2605132794 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1155 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2605132794 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Cairo</LOCATION>, 26 <DATE>May</DATE> (MENA) -- Arab League Secretary 
General Dr. 'Ismat 'Abd-al-Majid today received the credentials 
of Ambassador <PERSON>Ahmad Muhammad Luqman</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Yemen</LOCATION>'s new delegate to the 
<ORGANIZATION>Arab League</ORGANIZATION>, succeeding Ambassador Ahmad al-Shajni, who died 
recently. 
  Ambassador Luqman stated that he and the <ORGANIZATION>Arab League</ORGANIZATION> 
secretary general discussed several issues concerning ways to 
resolve the Yemeni crisis and said that the <ORGANIZATION>Arab League</ORGANIZATION> has 
resumed its mediation efforts to resolve the crisis. He noted 
that efforts are being made quietly to resolve the crisis within 
the context of the Yemeni Constitution. He said: In <LOCATION>Sanaa</LOCATION> we 
look at the situation from the viewpoint that a state exists and 
there are legitimate constitutional institutions chosen by the 
entire Yemeni people. Hence no party has the right to declare 
secession. 
  He described the current war in <LOCATION>Yemen</LOCATION> as one between the 
legitimate government and separatist rebel forces. 
  Asked about Yemeni President 'Ali '<PERSON>Abdallah Salih</PERSON>'s 
readiness 
for dialogue with the <LOCATION>Aden</LOCATION> leaders, <PERSON>Luqman</PERSON> said <LOCATION>Sanaa</LOCATION> has never 
stopped the dialogue, which continued throughout 'Ali Salim 
al-Bid's stay in <LOCATION>Aden</LOCATION>. He called for resorting to legitimacy 
and constitutional institutions. 
  Ambassador <PERSON>Ahmad Muhammad Luqman</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Yemen</LOCATION>'s new permanent 
delegate to the <ORGANIZATION>Arab League</ORGANIZATION>, was born in al-Hudaydah in <DATE>1948</DATE> and 
began his political career as deputy minister of social affairs 
from 1976-1980. He then became minister of state and secretary 
general of the <ORGANIZATION>Higher Council of Youths</ORGANIZATION> and Sports from 
1981-1983, minister of municipalities and housing from 
1983-1988, and minister of insurance and social affairs from 
1990-1993. 

</TEXT>

